data.content:
Yes — two improvements depending on your needs:

**1. Use `[DataRow]` for simple constants (simplest):**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. If you need computed/non-constant data, use strongly-typed tuples:**

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];

[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected((string Input, bool Expected) data)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(data.Input);
    Assert.AreEqual(data.Expected, result);
}
```

**Why these are better:**
- **`[DataRow]`** — no separate property needed, inline and readable. Best for literal values.
- **Typed tuples** — eliminates `object[]` casting, gives you named fields, and catches type mismatches at compile time.

Use `[DataRow]` when you can; fall back to `DynamicData` with tuples when test data needs to be computed or includes non-constant types.
